om a place called Aquino (see   D'Aquino  ), the place where the theologian (see 1 above) was born."],"variants":[{"name":"De Aquino","meanings":["Spanish and Portuguese (Brazil): variant of   Aquino  , a Christian personal name referring to Saint Thomas Aquinas (<i>Tomás de Aquino</i> in Spanish), with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘from, of’."]},{"name":"D'Aquino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Nicola, Stefano, Gaetano, Margherita, Nunzio, Sal, Salvatore.  Spanish Alba, Jose Alejandro, Pedro, Socorro.","Italian: habitational name for someone from a place called Aquino, of which there are several examples in Italy, but in particular the one in Lazio, birthplace of Saint Thomas Aquinas (see   Aquino  )."]},{"name":"Aguino","meanings":["Hispanic: habitational name from a place called Aguino in Oviedo (Asturias), or an altered form of Spanish   Aquino  . This surname is common among Native Americans (Pueblos) in NM. It is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Count","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earl","meanings":["North American: from the title originally adopted as a nickname parallel to   Duke  ,   King  , etc. The title was used in England in Norman times as an equivalent of the French <i>comte</i> ‘count’ it is from Old English <i>eorl</i> ‘warrior, nobleman, prince’. In some cases the given name may have been taken from the surname <i>Earl</i>, which was originally either a nickname or a term denoting someone who worked in the household of an earl."]}]},{"name":"Rinaldo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Reynold</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"Rainaldo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Reynold</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Count Rinaldo or Rainaldo D' Aquino was born in 1148 as the son of Conte Landone IV d'Aquino. He had at least 1 daughter with Cecilia di Medania. He died after 1160."},"et":{"1148?–after 1160":"1148–pärast 1160","1148–1160":"1148–1160","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1080":"1080","1148?":"1148","1313":"1313","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1157":"1157","after 1160":"pärast 1160","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Itaalia"},"fi":{"1148?–after 1160":"1148–1160 jälkeen","1148–1160":"1148–1160","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1148?":"1148","1313":"1313","1148":"1148","1125":"1125","1157":"1157","after 1160":"1160 jälkeen","1240":"1240","1160":"1160","Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italy":"Roccasecca, Roma, Lazio, Italia"},"fr":{"1148?–after 1160":"1148–après 1160","1148–1160":"1148–1160","1125–1157":"1125–1157","1240–1313":"1240–1313","1080–Male":"1080–Décédé","1080":"1080","1148?":"1148","1313":"1313","1148":"